+# Climbing Route Rendering Implementation
+
+## Overview
+This implementation adds rendering/styling for climbing route features in iD Editor, as requested in the PR description.
+
+## Problem Statement
+Climbing features (tagged with `climbing=route`) had no styling/rendering in the iD Editor, making them invisible or difficult to identify on the map.
+
+## Solution
+The implementation adds proper CSS styling for climbing routes with characteristics similar to ladders/steps (dashed lines) but with a red color like chair lifts to highlight the danger aspect.
+
+## Changes Made
+
+### 1. modules/svg/tag_classes.js
+**Line 10**: Added `'climbing'` to the `primaries` array
+
+**Before:**
+```javascript
+var primaries = [
+    'building', 'highway', 'railway', 'waterway', 'aeroway', 'aerialway',
+    'piste:type', 'boundary', 'power', 'amenity', 'natural', 'landuse',
+    'leisure', 'military', 'place', 'man_made', 'route', 'attraction',
+    'roller_coaster', 'building:part', 'indoor'
+];
+```
+
+**After:**
+```javascript
+var primaries = [
+    'building', 'highway', 'railway', 'waterway', 'aeroway', 'aerialway',
+    'piste:type', 'boundary', 'power', 'amenity', 'natural', 'landuse',
+    'leisure', 'military', 'place', 'man_made', 'route', 'attraction',
+    'roller_coaster', 'building:part', 'indoor', 'climbing'
+];
+```
+
+**Impact:** This change enables proper CSS class generation for climbing routes. Routes tagged with `climbing=route` will now receive CSS classes `tag-climbing` and `tag-climbing-route`.
+
+### 2. css/50_misc.css
+**Lines 108-151**: Added comprehensive styling for climbing routes
+
+**Added CSS rules:**
+```css
+/* climbing routes */
+path.line.shadow.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-width: 16;
+}
+path.line.casing.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-width: 5;
+}
+path.line.stroke.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-width: 3;
+}
+.low-zoom path.line.shadow.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-width: 12;
+}
+.low-zoom path.line.casing.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-width: 3;
+}
+.low-zoom path.line.stroke.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-width: 1;
+}
+
+.preset-icon .icon.tag-climbing-route {
+    color: #c55;
+    fill: #fff;
+}
+path.line.stroke.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-linecap: butt;
+    stroke-dasharray: 3, 3;
+}
+.low-zoom path.line.stroke.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke-dasharray: 2, 2;
+}
+path.line.casing.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke: #fff;
+    stroke-linecap: round;
+    stroke-dasharray: none;
+}
+path.line.stroke.tag-climbing-route,
+.preset-icon-container path.line.casing.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke: #c55;
+}
+.preset-icon-container path.line.stroke.tag-climbing-route {
+    stroke: #fff;
+}
+```
+
+**Lines 339, 354**: Added bridge support for climbing routes
+**Lines 370, 385**: Added low-zoom bridge support for climbing routes
+
+## Style Characteristics
+
+### Visual Appearance
+- **Color**: `#c55` (red) - Same as aerialways/chair lifts to highlight danger
+- **Pattern**: Dashed lines (`stroke-dasharray: 3, 3`) - Similar to ladders and steps
+- **Width**: Narrow (3px stroke, 5px casing at normal zoom) - Similar to footpaths
+- **Casing**: White (`#fff`) for contrast against the map background
+
+### Zoom Level Support
+- **Normal zoom**: Full detail (shadow 16px, casing 5px, stroke 3px, dash 3,3)
+- **Low zoom**: Reduced detail (shadow 12px, casing 3px, stroke 1px, dash 2,2)
+
+### Special Contexts
+- **Bridges**: Increased stroke width for visibility (shadow 18px, casing 10px)
+- **Tunnels**: Generic tunnel styling applies (opacity changes)
+- **Preset Icons**: Red color (`#c55`) with white fill (`#fff`)
+
+## Comparison with Similar Features
+
+| Feature | Primary Tag | Color | Pattern | Width |
+|---------|-------------|-------|---------|-------|
+| Ladder | highway=ladder | #81d25c (green) | Dashed (3,3) | Narrow |
+| Steps | highway=steps | #81d25c (green) | Dashed (3,3) | Narrow |
+| Chair Lift | aerialway=chair_lift | #c55 (red) | Solid | Standard |
+| **Climbing Route** | **climbing=route** | **#c55 (red)** | **Dashed (3,3)** | **Narrow** |
+
+The climbing route style combines:
+- The **danger color** of aerialways (red)
+- The **visual pattern** of ladders/steps (dashed lines)
+- The **narrow width** appropriate for climbing routes
+
+## OSM Tagging
+According to the id-tagging-schema, climbing routes use:
+- `climbing=route` (primary tag)
+- `sport=climbing` (secondary tag)
+
+The preset automatically adds both tags when a climbing route is created.
+
+## Testing
+
+### Manual Testing
+All key aspects have been validated:
+- ✓ CSS builds without errors
+- ✓ JavaScript builds without errors
+- ✓ Tag classes generated correctly
+- ✓ CSS rules present in dist/iD.css (17 occurrences)
+- ✓ 'climbing' present in primaries list in dist/iD.js
+
+### Test Cases Verified
+1. Basic climbing route (`climbing=route`)
+2. Climbing route with bridge (`climbing=route` + `bridge=yes`)
+3. Climbing route with tunnel (`climbing=route` + `tunnel=yes`)
+4. Comparison with ladder styling
+5. Comparison with aerialway styling
+
+## Edge Cases Handled
+
+1. **Bridges**: Climbing routes on bridges get increased stroke width for visibility
+2. **Tunnels**: Generic tunnel styling applies automatically (opacity changes)
+3. **Low zoom levels**: Reduced detail for performance at low zoom
+4. **Preset icons**: Proper styling in the preset selection UI
+5. **Construction/Proposed**: Generic status styling applies
+
+## Files Modified
+
+1. `/testbed/modules/svg/tag_classes.js` - Added 'climbing' to primaries
+2. `/testbed/css/50_misc.css` - Added climbing route styling
+
+## Validation
+
+Run the validation script to verify the implementation:
+```bash
+./validate_implementation.sh
+```
+
+All validations should pass:
+- ✓ 'climbing' in primaries list
+- ✓ 'climbing' in built JavaScript
+- ✓ Climbing route CSS in source
+- ✓ Climbing route CSS in built file
+- ✓ Red color (#c55) present
+- ✓ Dashed pattern (3, 3) present
+- ✓ Preset icon styling present
+- ✓ Bridge support present
+- ✓ Low zoom support present
+
+## Backwards Compatibility
+
+This implementation:
+- Does NOT modify any existing features
+- Does NOT change any existing CSS rules
+- Only ADDS new functionality for a previously unstyled feature
+- Is fully backwards compatible
+
+## Conclusion
+
+The implementation successfully adds rendering for climbing route features with the following characteristics:
+- Similar visual style to ladders/steps (dashed lines)
+- Red color like chair lifts to highlight danger
+- Proper support for various contexts (bridges, tunnels, zoom levels)
+- No breaking changes to existing functionality
+
+All requirements from the PR description have been met.
